Loan Data Exploration¶

by Cyril Odoi

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing key requirements for credit application for approximately 114,000 loan applications.

Assessments¶

  1. Filter out missing values in DebtToIncomeRatio, ProsperScore, BorrowerState, Occupation, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration columns.
  2. Update datatypes for the following: Listing category from numeric to Categorical datatype, Listing Number from integer to string, LoanOriginationDate to Datetime (extract year, month, day and time Loan originated), LoanStatus from string to categorical, IncomeRange from integer to Categorical datatype, EmploymentStatus from string to Categorical.
  3. Change 'EmploymentStatusDuration' column name to 'EmploymentStatusDuration(Months)' to make more descriptive.
  4. Change 'Term' column name to 'LoanDuration(Months) to make more descriptive.
  5. Round StatedMonthlyIncome to whole dollars figures.
  6. Replace IsBorrowerHomeowner values with 'Yes' and 'No' and change datatype to categorical.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 77,543 rows of loan data in the dataset with 17 columns (ListingNumber, LoanDuration, LoanStatus, IncomeRange, ProsperScore, ListingCategory, BorrowerState, Occupation, EmploymentStatus, EmploymentStatusDuration, DebtToIncomeRatio, IsBorrowerHomeowner, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate, LoanOriginationQuarter, MonthlyLoanPayment).

There is a good mix of numerical and categorical data. (best) ——> (worst) LoanStatus: Completed, FinalPaymentInProgress, Current, Chargedoff, Past Due (1-15 days), Past Due (16-30 days), Past Due (31-60 days),Past Due (61-90 days) Past Due (91-120 days), Past Due (>120 days), Defaulted. ProsperScore: 10,9,8..,1

What are the main features of interest in your dataset?¶

I am curious to find out what factors come to play to determine creditworthiness of a potential Borrower

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation of creditworthiness?¶

I strongly believe the following characteristics will factor greatly in potential creditworthiness: ProsperScore, BorrowerRate, StatedMonthlyIncome, DebtToIncomeRatio and LoanOriginalAmount.

#creating a fuction that plots seaborn countplots
def Countplot(df, xvar, huevar=None, color=0, palette=None, order=None):
    #set plot dimentions
    plt.figure(figsize = [14,6])
    #plot
    sb.countplot(data=loan_copy, x='IsBorrowerHomeowner', hue=huevar, color=sb.color_palette()[0], palette=palette, order=order, edgecolor='black')
    #clean up variable names
    xvar = xvar.replace("_"," ")
    if huevar:
        huevar = huevar.replace("_"," ")
    #add title and format it
    plt.title(f"Distribution of Borrower Homeownership Status: {xvar} {'by' if huevar else ''} {huevar if huevar else ''}" .title(), fontsize=18, weight='bold')
    #add x label and format it
    plt.xlabel('Is Borrower a Homeowner?', fontsize=13, weight='bold')
    #add y label and format it
    plt.ylabel('Borrower Count', fontsize=13, weight='bold');

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset¶

  1. Loan Duration did not factor highly in Borrower rate received as initially expected.
  2. Prosper Scores played a huge role in lowering the Borrower Rate received by borrowers
  3. For the most part, Borrowers who owned homes were approved for larger loans than borrowers without homes.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I initially thought longer term loans would carry higher borrower rates to factor for risk, but the analysis showed that effect of loan duration was not as impactful on borrower rate.

Conclusions:¶

From this analysis, I can confidently conclude majority of loans were issued in the year 2013. I discovered that for a Large Loan the Loan Duration is 36 or 60 months.

To be granted access to these large loans, Borrower needs to have a Debt-To-Income-Ratio of less than 1.0.

Prosper Scores of 8 or better is crucial to being approved for a loan. Borrower Rates increase as Prosper Scores of borrowers worsened. Homeowners enjoyed a higher probability of being approved for a loan due to their home being a good source of collateral.
